Part 1: Quantization¶

  • Insert your function quant_img(img, N) from the preliminary report.
In [3]:
def quant_img (img,N):
    #uniform quantization of an image to values [0,N]
    min_val=np.min(img)
    max_val=np.max(img)
    quant_range=(max_val-min_val)/N
    quant_uniform=min_val + np.floor((quant_range*np.floor_divide(img-min_val,quant_range)))
    #explanation: we normalize the values of the image to the window quant_uniform, and round down
    return quant_uniform

In [10]:
def imnoise(img, mean, std):
    noisy_img = img + np.random.normal(mean, std, img.shape)
    return np.clip(noisy_img, 0, 255)  # keep the bounds
In [19]:

plt.show()

We can see that noise reduces the False Contours problem. The optimal s.d. value is 7, below this value the noise is not significant enough to unsmooth the original image and above this value the noise overkill the image.

  • Bonus exercise - perform quantization on your image by using K-means to 2, 4, 8, 16, 32 and 64 gray levels.
    Compare your results to the results from the previous section.
In [20]:
m,n = img.shape

quant_levels = [2,4,8,16,32,64]
fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=2, ncols=int(len(quant_levels)/2))
ax = axes.ravel()

for num,N in enumerate(quant_levels):
    np.random.seed(0)

    image_array = img.reshape(-1,1)
    image_array_sample = shuffle(image_array, random_state=0)[:1000]
    kmeans = cluster.KMeans(n_clusters= N).fit(image_array_sample)   
    
    labels = kmeans.predict(image_array)


    image = np.zeros((m,n))
    label_idx = 0
    for i in range(m):
        for j in range(n):
            image[i][j] = kmeans.cluster_centers_[labels[label_idx]]
            label_idx += 1
    ax[num].imshow(image, cmap='gray')
    ax[num].set_title("Quantization of {} levels".format(N))
    
plt.tight_layout(pad =0.05,w_pad=4)
plt.show()

We can see that the false contours problem appears for quantazation levels up to 16 levels, a better result compared to the uniform quantization we did earlier. Though the quality of the images looks not as good as the uniform quantiazation method.

Part 2: Color Histogram Equalization¶

Use the supplied function hist_demo().

  • Observe the following demonstrations:
    • Contrast stretching.
    • Histogram equalization.
In [49]:
def hist_demo(img):
    # Contrast stretching
    img_dbl = np.float64(img)
    min_im = np.min(np.min(img_dbl))
    max_im = np.max(np.max(img_dbl))
    img_stretched_contrast = np.uint8(255*(img_dbl-min_im)/(max_im-min_im))
    
    # Histogram equalization
    img_hist_eq = cv2.equalizeHist(img) 
    
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=1, ncols=2)
    ax = axes.ravel()
    ax[0].imshow(img, cmap='gray')
    ax[0].set_title("Original image")
    hist = cv2.calcHist([img],[0],None,[256],[0,256])
    ax[1].plot(hist)
    ax[1].set_title("Original image histogram")  
    plt.tight_layout(); plt.show()
    
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=1, ncols=2)
    ax = axes.ravel()
    ax[0].imshow(img_stretched_contrast, cmap='gray')
    ax[0].set_title("Contrast stretching image")
    hist = cv2.calcHist([img_stretched_contrast],[0],None,[256],[0,256])
    ax[1].plot(hist)
    ax[1].set_title("Contrast stretching histogram")
    plt.tight_layout(); plt.show()
    
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=1, ncols=2)
    ax = axes.ravel()
    ax[0].imshow(img_hist_eq, cmap='gray')
    ax[0].set_title("Histogram equalization image")
    hist = cv2.calcHist([img_hist_eq],[0],None,[256],[0,256])
    ax[1].plot(hist)
    ax[1].set_title("Histogram equalization histogram")
    plt.tight_layout(); plt.show()

  • Load a gray image of your choise and test these demonstrations. Make sure that the image you choose is indeed affected by both operations.

In [54]:
img2=plt.imread("fog.jpg")
img2=color.rgb2gray(img2)
img2=img_as_ubyte(img2)

hist_demo(img2)

Contrast steching is not good for images where grey levels are spread through the entire grey level range in their histogram (i.e. images with already high contrast). We can see that for this fogged image, the histogram equalization and contrast streching method reveal a few new deatails in the image. Histogram equalization will not effect the image if the common grey values are already far away from each other (i.e. the histogram is uniformly distributed).

Histogram Equalization

  1. Show the histogram-equalized color image. In this case, the histogram equalization is performed separately on all 3 layers (R, G, B). Use the supplied function hist_eq_rgb.

Note: In this section you should load a color image.

In [55]:
# Supplied function - 
def hist_eq_rgb(img):
    
    print("image shape: ", img.shape)
    plt.imshow(img)
    plt.show()
    R, G, B = cv2.split(img)
    R_eq = cv2.equalizeHist(R)
    G_eq = cv2.equalizeHist(G)
    B_eq = cv2.equalizeHist(B)

    
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(ncols=4, nrows=3, figsize=(30, 20))
    ax[0,0].imshow(R); ax[0,0].set_title('Red channel')
    ax[1,0].imshow(G); ax[1,0].set_title('Green channel')
    ax[2,0].imshow(B); ax[2,0].set_title('Blue channel')
    ax[0,1].hist(R.flatten(),256,[0,256], color = 'r'); ax[0,1].set_title('Red channel histogram')
    ax[1,1].hist(G.flatten(),256,[0,256], color = 'b'); ax[1,1].set_title('Green channel histogram')
    ax[2,1].hist(B.flatten(),256,[0,256], color = 'g'); ax[2,1].set_title('Blue channel histogram')
    
    ax[0,2].imshow(R_eq); ax[0,2].set_title('Red channel after histogram equalization')
    ax[1,2].imshow(G_eq); ax[1,2].set_title('Green channel after histogram equalization')
    ax[2,2].imshow(B_eq); ax[2,2].set_title('Blue channel after histogram equalization')
    ax[0,3].hist(R_eq.flatten(),256,[0,256], color = 'r');ax[0,3].set_title('Red channel histogram after histogram equalization')
    ax[1,3].hist(G_eq.flatten(),256,[0,256], color = 'b');ax[1,3].set_title('Green channel histogram after histogram equalization')
    ax[2,3].hist(B_eq.flatten(),256,[0,256], color = 'g');ax[2,3].set_title('Blue channel histogram after histogram equalization')
    
    
    
    img_eq = cv2.merge((R_eq,G_eq,B_eq))
    plt.figure()
    
    plt.imshow(img_eq)
    plt.title('The image after histogram equalization on all 3 layers (R, G, B)')
    plt.show()

  1. Perform histogram equalization each time on one of the H, S, V components (the other 2 components remain unchanged), generating 3 color images. (Hint: in order to display on the monitor the color image that was created in HSV space, you have to convert the image back to RGB space).
In [60]:
img3=cv2.imread("lighthouse.bmp")
img3=cv2.cvtColor(img3,cv2.COLOR_BGR2HSV)
H, S, V = cv2.split(img3)
H_eq = cv2.equalizeHist(H)
S_eq = cv2.equalizeHist(S)
V_eq = cv2.equalizeHist(V)
img_h_eq = cv2.merge((H_eq,S,V))
img_h_eq=cv2.cvtColor(img_h_eq,cv2.COLOR_HSV2RGB)
img_s_eq = cv2.merge((H,S_eq,V))
img_s_eq=cv2.cvtColor(img_s_eq,cv2.COLOR_HSV2RGB)
img_v_eq = cv2.merge((H,S,V_eq))
img_v_eq=cv2.cvtColor(img_v_eq,cv2.COLOR_HSV2RGB)
plt.imshow(img_h_eq)
plt.show()
plt.imshow(img_s_eq)
plt.show()
plt.imshow(img_v_eq)
plt.show()
  1. which method is better for performing an histogram equaliztion?

The historgram equalization on the V component is better, is keeps the original colors of the image and have better brightness. the other 2 equalizations change the colors of the original or oversaturating the image.
